WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:13.210
JESS: Hi, everyone.

00:00:13.210 --> 00:00:13.710
Hello.

00:00:13.710 --> 00:00:16.090
Welcome to Authors at Google.

00:00:16.090 --> 00:00:18.470
So, as you all know,
over the past decade,

00:00:18.470 --> 00:00:22.132
Steve Jobs has changed
the way that we

00:00:22.132 --> 00:00:23.965
think about giving
presentations by modeling

00:00:23.965 --> 00:00:28.441
a new form of interaction
types of presentations.

00:00:28.441 --> 00:00:30.480
Today, we are going to
hear from the man that

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:32.549
taught the world how
to be like Steve Jobs.

00:00:32.549 --> 00:00:36.525
He has watched hundreds of
hours of footage of TED talks,

00:00:36.525 --> 00:00:39.047
and today, he's doing
it again-- teaching

00:00:39.047 --> 00:00:40.640
us all how to talk like TED.

00:00:43.175 --> 00:00:44.070
Carmine Gallo.

00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:44.530
CARMINE GALLO:All right.

00:00:44.530 --> 00:00:45.071
Thanks, Jess.

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:49.080
Good afternoon.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:50.490
Hello, everyone.

00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:54.150
I feel like I have a lot
of microphones on me today.

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:58.380
There's multiple streams going
on, and that's why the mics.

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:01.980
This is such an honor for
me to be speaking at Google.

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:04.830
First of all, thank you
for changing the world.

00:01:04.830 --> 00:01:07.370
That's astonishing and must
be an amazing experience

00:01:07.370 --> 00:01:08.261
to work here.

00:01:08.261 --> 00:01:10.260
That's what I want to
talk to you about today is

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:12.450
world changing ideas.

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:15.190
How many of you have good ideas?

00:01:15.190 --> 00:01:17.790
How many of you think
you've got a good idea?

00:01:17.790 --> 00:01:19.290
OK, most of you.

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:22.230
Your ideas are
your currency now.

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:26.430
Your ideas are the currency
of the 21st century.

00:01:26.430 --> 00:01:29.160
In the information age,
the knowledge economy,

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:32.570
you're only as successful
as your ability

00:01:32.570 --> 00:01:36.160
to communicate your
ideas persuasively.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:37.280
How do you do that?

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:40.690
I believe that there are
three fundamental laws

00:01:40.690 --> 00:01:44.450
of communications-- laws that I
learned after studying hundreds

00:01:44.450 --> 00:01:49.080
and hundreds of TED talks and
also analyzing and interviewing

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:52.070
some of the most famous
TED presenters of our time.

00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:55.740
Now, it's not just me who says
that communication skills are

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:56.520
so important.

00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:58.930
Ben Horowitz is a very
well-known local venture

00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:00.340
capitalist.

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.670
With Andreessen Horowitz, who's
behind Facebook and Twitter

00:02:03.670 --> 00:02:07.018
and many other companies as
well, and obviously many of you

00:02:07.018 --> 00:02:09.699
know him as a
substantial investor.

00:02:09.699 --> 00:02:12.970
He was at South by Southwest
and he gave us this quote.

00:02:12.970 --> 00:02:16.800
"Storytelling is the
most underrated skill

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:18.360
when it comes to
entrepreneurship."

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:21.230
he was speaking specifically
to entrepreneurs.

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:27.980
Storytelling-- the ability to
tell your story convincingly,

00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:31.340
persuasively, in a way
that really engages me--

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:32.970
that's going to be your value.

00:02:32.970 --> 00:02:37.090
That's going to help you
stand out in all of the noise

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:40.170
and to stand out and move your
brand forward and your careers

00:02:40.170 --> 00:02:41.760
forward.

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:43.210
Ben Horowitz believes that.

00:02:43.210 --> 00:02:45.040
I certainly believe that.

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:47.010
And this gentleman
believes that.

00:02:47.010 --> 00:02:49.020
You may have seen him
before-- Warren Buffett,

00:02:49.020 --> 00:02:50.610
the billionaire.

00:02:50.610 --> 00:02:53.870
Listen to this
audio clip where he

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:56.460
is telling a group of
business students--

00:02:56.460 --> 00:02:58.720
I believe this was
Columbia University--

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:00.750
he's talking to a group
of business students.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:04.430
Listen to the value
that he places

00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:07.934
on communication skills
and public speaking.

00:03:07.934 --> 00:03:08.600
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:13.279
-Right now I would
pay $100,000 for 10%

00:03:13.279 --> 00:03:14.820
of the future earnings
of any of you.

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:16.861
So if anyone wants to see
me after this is over--

00:03:16.861 --> 00:03:19.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:24.092 --> 00:03:26.686
If that's true, if you're a
million-dollar asset right now,

00:03:26.686 --> 00:03:29.342
right, if 10% of you
is worth $100,000?

00:03:29.342 --> 00:03:31.583
You could improve-- many
of you, and I certainly

00:03:31.583 --> 00:03:35.152
could have when I got
out, just in terms

00:03:35.152 --> 00:03:36.812
of learning
communication skills.

00:03:36.812 --> 00:03:38.306
It's not something
that is taught.

00:03:38.306 --> 00:03:39.924
I actually went to a
Dale Carnegie course

00:03:39.924 --> 00:03:41.044
later on in terms
of public speaking.

00:03:41.044 --> 00:03:43.784
But if you improve your value
50% by having communication

00:03:43.784 --> 00:03:47.270
skills, that's another $500,000
in terms of capital value.

00:03:47.270 --> 00:03:50.756
See me after the class
and I'll pay you $150,000.

00:03:50.756 --> 00:03:53.420
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:55.400
CARMINE GALLO: Why
would he say that?

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:59.050
Because Daniel Pink, a noted
author, has recently observed,

00:03:59.050 --> 00:04:01.700
"like it or not, we're
all in sales now."

00:04:01.700 --> 00:04:04.180
That means that
you are constantly

00:04:04.180 --> 00:04:07.640
selling yourself and selling
your ideas internally

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:09.700
and externally.

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:11.130
It's the 21st century.

00:04:11.130 --> 00:04:13.980
We have new models of
communication, don't we?

00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:19.950
We communicate in photos,
videos, 140-character tweets.

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:23.950
Well, I believe that a 21st
century model of communication

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:27.370
requires 21st century
techniques, which

00:04:27.370 --> 00:04:31.720
is why I turned my lens
from Steve Jobs, who

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:35.830
was one individual-- and
in my opinion, the greatest

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:38.050
corporate storyteller
we've ever had--

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:42.800
and I turned my focus
onto TED, the TED talks.

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:45.530
TED, even though I'm
independent, I'm objective,

00:04:45.530 --> 00:04:48.520
I'm not affiliated
with that conference,

00:04:48.520 --> 00:04:50.570
I've worked with
many TED speakers.

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:52.050
I've interviewed TED speakers.

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:55.175
I've analyzed 150 hours
worth of TED content

00:04:55.175 --> 00:04:57.120
and I've categorized it.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:01.740
And I think I know why the
best TED talks go viral.

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:04.450
But more importantly for
all of us in the room

00:05:04.450 --> 00:05:07.850
is what can we learn
from the world's greatest

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:11.290
presenters and speakers
that we can apply

00:05:11.290 --> 00:05:15.800
to make our message, our
pitch, more persuasive, more

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:16.590
convincing?

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:18.710
Especially if you
only have-- let's

00:05:18.710 --> 00:05:20.120
say you don't have 18 minutes.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:22.300
You have five minutes
to convince your boss

00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:23.690
to back your idea.

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:25.160
How do you get it across?

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:26.210
How do you persuade?

00:05:26.210 --> 00:05:28.350
That's what we're going
to talk about today.

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:32.540
I believe that there are
three fundamental components

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:36.260
that all inspirational
communication has.

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:39.790
Any time there is a
conversation, a presentation,

00:05:39.790 --> 00:05:44.230
a pitch that we
consider persuasive,

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:47.140
these are the three
components that they have.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:51.470
They are emotional-- that
conversation is emotional.

00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:54.660
You have to touch my heart
before you reach my head.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:57.360
Those conversations are novel.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:59.610
They teach me something new.

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:01.830
And finally, they're
also memorable.

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:03.140
It doesn't matter.

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:06.579
Your idea doesn't matter if I
can't remember what you said.

00:06:06.579 --> 00:06:08.620
So we're going to talk
about each one one by one.

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:09.960
Let's talk about emotional.

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:13.360
How do we make ideas emotional?

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:14.370
First, passion.

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:16.220
Passion is everything.

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:19.290
You cannot inspire unless
you're inspired yourself.

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:21.000
It's also important
for your career.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.740
Dr. Larry Smith gave a
very famous TEDx event.

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:29.540
He is a University of
Waterloo economics professor.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:33.150
He's been studying passion and
entrepreneurship for decades.

00:06:33.150 --> 00:06:36.890
And he says passion is
the thing, the thing that

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:42.210
will help you create the highest
expression of your talent.

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:45.020
I asked him after his TED
talk, I asked Dr. Smith,

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:46.710
how do you identify passion?

00:06:46.710 --> 00:06:49.146
This all sounds good,
and I agree with it.

00:06:49.146 --> 00:06:50.270
But how do you identify it?

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:52.450
What is it when we
say, that person

00:06:52.450 --> 00:06:53.850
is passionate about something?

00:06:53.850 --> 00:06:55.210
I want to follow my passion.

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:56.880
That sounds so cliche.

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:59.040
What exactly does that mean.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:04.110
He pointed me to an excerpt
from his now-famous TED talk,

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:07.060
and here's what he says
about what passion means.

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.263
Probably the best
definition I've heard.

00:07:09.263 --> 00:07:10.742
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:10.742 --> 00:07:12.714
-Passion is your greatest love.

00:07:12.714 --> 00:07:18.040
Passion is the thing that will
help you create the highest

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.123
expression of your talent.

00:07:19.123 --> 00:07:22.468
Passion, interest, it's
not the same thing.

00:07:22.468 --> 00:07:24.217
Are you really going
to go to your sweetie

00:07:24.217 --> 00:07:27.011
and say, marry me,
if you're interested?

00:07:31.448 --> 00:07:33.913
Won't happen.

00:07:33.913 --> 00:07:36.378
Won't happen, and
you will die alone.

00:07:36.378 --> 00:07:37.364
What you want.

00:07:37.364 --> 00:07:39.050
What you want.

00:07:39.050 --> 00:07:41.426
What you want is passion.

00:07:41.426 --> 00:07:43.886
It is beyond interest.

00:07:43.886 --> 00:07:47.576
You need 20 interests, and
then one of them, one of them

00:07:47.576 --> 00:07:48.806
might grab you.

00:07:48.806 --> 00:07:51.226
One of them may engage you
more than anything else,

00:07:51.226 --> 00:07:53.726
and then you may have found
your greatest love in comparison

00:07:53.726 --> 00:07:58.154
to all the other things
that interest you.

00:07:58.154 --> 00:07:59.630
And that's what passion is.

00:07:59.630 --> 00:08:00.650
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:08:00.650 --> 00:08:02.810
CARMINE GALLO: OK,
your greatest love.

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:05.150
By the way, he's really
passionate, isn't he?

00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:06.100
He's worked up.

00:08:06.100 --> 00:08:09.280
And I asked him, Dr. Smith,
you're going nuts on this.

00:08:09.280 --> 00:08:10.160
What's happening?

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:11.740
He said, Carmine,
what you have seen

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:14.830
is 40 years of
pent-up frustration,

00:08:14.830 --> 00:08:17.640
of telling people that
they need to follow

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:20.270
their passion in order
to create the highest

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:21.670
expression of their talent.

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:25.140
And he said, Carmine, wasted
talent is a waste I cannot

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:28.200
stand, which is why passion
is so important to him.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:31.590
But I love that definition--
your greatest love.

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:33.130
How does that relate to us?

00:08:33.130 --> 00:08:36.140
How does that relate to,
say, entrepreneurship?

00:08:36.140 --> 00:08:40.530
I write for "Forbes," also
the books that I write.

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:45.490
I have this amazing opportunity
to interview and spend time

00:08:45.490 --> 00:08:47.820
with some of the great
leaders of our time.

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:51.110
Let's talk about this idea
of your greatest love,

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:53.510
and what does that mean
to follow your passion?

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:56.690
Here's a photograph of
me and Richard Branson.

00:08:56.690 --> 00:08:58.590
Richard Branson always
seems to be smiling.

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:01.710
I think when you've got five
billion reasons to smile,

00:09:01.710 --> 00:09:02.920
you're always happy.

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:04.650
He's always happy.

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:07.350
But when I asked him,
what's your greatest love?

00:09:07.350 --> 00:09:11.270
It's not-- it's not
getting people from point A

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:12.842
to point B on an airplane.

00:09:12.842 --> 00:09:14.050
That's not his greatest love.

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:18.350
His greatest love is
disrupting the status quo.

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:20.790
It's elevating the
customer experience.

00:09:20.790 --> 00:09:23.230
Some of you are familiar
with Zappos, I'm sure.

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:25.340
Tony Hsieh, who's sort
of elevated the customer

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:27.020
experience, speaking of that.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:28.470
I've interviewed Tony Hsieh.

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:31.090
His greatest love
is not the shoes,

00:09:31.090 --> 00:09:33.030
which is very interesting.

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:36.370
He sells shoes online,
but he wears old shoes

00:09:36.370 --> 00:09:37.900
till they're worn out.

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:40.090
When I asked him, what's
your greatest love?

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:41.730
He never mentioned shoes.

00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:43.820
He says it's
delivering happiness.

00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:48.680
How can I deliver happiness to
my customers and my employees?

00:09:48.680 --> 00:09:51.930
Which is why he's created
that great culture at Zappos,

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:56.120
a culture like many of you have
experienced here at Google.

00:09:56.120 --> 00:09:57.940
The point is, he's
always thinking.

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:01.170
The most inspiring
communicators and entrepreneurs

00:10:01.170 --> 00:10:04.290
don't really pitch
their product as much

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:06.950
as they pitch what
the product means

00:10:06.950 --> 00:10:09.580
for the lives of
their customers.

00:10:09.580 --> 00:10:12.590
Big difference.

00:10:12.590 --> 00:10:16.080
Howard Schultz, the founder
of Starbucks-- actually,

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:17.130
they he's the founder.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:19.550
No, he's the CEO of
Starbucks, and he's

00:10:19.550 --> 00:10:22.220
going to explain in a video
clip I'm going to show.

00:10:22.220 --> 00:10:24.780
But Howard Schultz,
when I interviewed him,

00:10:24.780 --> 00:10:28.970
completely changed the way I
look at communication skills.

00:10:28.970 --> 00:10:32.540
This was several years
ago for one of my books.

00:10:32.540 --> 00:10:35.310
He spent two hours
with me and not

00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:37.850
once did he talk about coffee.

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:40.170
I was the one who
brought up coffee.

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:43.010
That's because that's
not what he's selling.

00:10:43.010 --> 00:10:46.900
He's selling a better
customer experience.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:49.720
He is selling a workplace
that treats people

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:51.060
with dignity and respect.

00:10:51.060 --> 00:10:54.320
He's selling community
and the romance of coffee,

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:56.660
but it's not about the coffee.

00:10:56.660 --> 00:10:58.900
It's so much deeper than that.

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:01.050
He gave me a quote
that I'll never forget.

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:05.620
He said, Carmine, coffee is
the product that we make,

00:11:05.620 --> 00:11:07.750
but it's not the
business we're in.

00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:10.010
So you need to think about that.

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:11.340
That blew my mind.

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:13.630
I can't tell you what--
I mean, it completely

00:11:13.630 --> 00:11:16.179
changed the way I
look at communication.

00:11:16.179 --> 00:11:17.970
You've got to think
about not your product,

00:11:17.970 --> 00:11:19.550
but what business you're in.

00:11:19.550 --> 00:11:26.050
This week, Oprah Winfrey
created her first big product

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:28.210
partnership with Starbucks.

00:11:28.210 --> 00:11:30.410
I think it's the Teavana brand.

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:32.340
Some of you may have that tea.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:34.550
It was her first big
product partnership,

00:11:34.550 --> 00:11:38.710
and she decided to go on a
partnership with Howard Schultz

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:42.660
because-- and I'm paraphrasing--
but she said because Starbucks

00:11:42.660 --> 00:11:44.590
is so much more than a company.

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:46.570
It's so much more
than the coffee.

00:11:46.570 --> 00:11:48.740
It means so much more.

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:49.900
That comes from him.

00:11:49.900 --> 00:11:52.430
That comes from the
entrepreneur, the leader,

00:11:52.430 --> 00:11:55.390
and the way he communicates
the vision behind his brand.

00:11:55.390 --> 00:11:59.310
Watch this very short video
clip taken a few months ago

00:11:59.310 --> 00:12:02.290
of Oprah Winfrey first
interviewing Howard Schultz.

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:05.392
Listen to the way he
talks about the brand.

00:12:05.392 --> 00:12:06.384
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:06.384 --> 00:12:08.191
-People think I'm the
founder of Starbucks,

00:12:08.191 --> 00:12:09.690
but I'm was an
employee of Starbucks

00:12:09.690 --> 00:12:10.848
when they had four stores.

00:12:10.848 --> 00:12:14.816
I was sent to Italy to
do a trip for Starbucks.

00:12:14.816 --> 00:12:17.296
I came back with this
feeling that the business

00:12:17.296 --> 00:12:19.881
that Starbucks was in
was the wrong business.

00:12:19.881 --> 00:12:22.256
-Because at the time that you
were employed by Starbucks,

00:12:22.256 --> 00:12:25.232
they just sold coffee
beans, and they actually

00:12:25.232 --> 00:12:27.216
did not sell a cup of coffee.

00:12:27.216 --> 00:12:28.208
-That's correct.

00:12:28.208 --> 00:12:30.192
And so what I
wanted to bring back

00:12:30.192 --> 00:12:33.168
was the daily ritual and
the sense of community,

00:12:33.168 --> 00:12:36.888
and the idea that we could build
this third place between home

00:12:36.888 --> 00:12:38.624
and work in America.

00:12:38.624 --> 00:12:40.608
-Can you take me back
to that little coffee

00:12:40.608 --> 00:12:42.592
shop and the feeling
you had there?

00:12:42.592 --> 00:12:43.584
-In Italy?

00:12:43.584 --> 00:12:46.560
-Yes, absolutely,
when I was reading it,

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:49.536
it felt like an [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:49.536 --> 00:12:51.520
-I was out of my mind.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:53.008
Every--

00:12:53.008 --> 00:12:54.992
-Had you gone in for coffee?

00:12:54.992 --> 00:12:56.480
-Yeah, like anyone else.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:13:02.330
But I walked in and saw
this symphony, the romance

00:13:02.330 --> 00:13:06.218
and the theater of coffee.

00:13:06.218 --> 00:13:10.592
And also, coffee can be a
center of conversation socially.

00:13:10.592 --> 00:13:12.374
That is what spoke
to me, and that's

00:13:12.374 --> 00:13:13.647
what I wanted to achieve.

00:13:13.647 --> 00:13:14.480
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:17.220
CARMINE GALLO: Coffee at
the center of conversation.

00:13:17.220 --> 00:13:18.670
You see how it goes?

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:20.620
His communication
about his brand

00:13:20.620 --> 00:13:24.280
goes so far beyond just
the physical product.

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:26.870
Passion, by the
way, is contagious.

00:13:26.870 --> 00:13:30.900
I did a lot of research into
the science of persuasion

00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:32.670
for my new TED book,
and I interviewed

00:13:32.670 --> 00:13:34.930
neuroscientists and researchers.

00:13:34.930 --> 00:13:38.110
What they're finding is that
passion is indeed contagious.

00:13:38.110 --> 00:13:40.460
We already know
this intuitively,

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:44.050
but they are finding that if
you meet someone or listen

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:46.780
to someone who is genuinely
and authentically--

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:51.640
those are important words--
genuinely enthusiastic

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:53.840
about their product
and what it means

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:55.800
for the lives of
their customers,

00:13:55.800 --> 00:14:00.040
that it will significantly
alter your perception

00:14:00.040 --> 00:14:01.890
of that person and that product.

00:14:01.890 --> 00:14:03.840
So you've got to
think about passion.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:05.510
How do we transfer that passion?

00:14:05.510 --> 00:14:08.430
How do we transfer what
we're excited about?

00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:11.160
That's where we have to master
the art of storytelling.

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:15.180
All of the greatest presenters
in corporate America

00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:18.560
today, and certainly on the
TED stage, are fantastic

00:14:18.560 --> 00:14:19.980
storytellers.

00:14:19.980 --> 00:14:23.080
Research is finding
some remarkable things.

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.170
A remarkable thing happens
to your brain on stories.

00:14:27.170 --> 00:14:29.060
Princeton University
researchers have

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:32.310
found that if I
tell you a story,

00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:36.020
the same areas of our
brains-- if they take an MRI

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:41.500
scan to look at brain blood
flow-- the same areas light up.

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:44.350
That means we are
literally in sync.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:47.470
They call it
mind-to-mind coupling.

00:14:47.470 --> 00:14:49.360
I just call it being in sync.

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:51.100
Stories are powerful.

00:14:51.100 --> 00:14:53.570
Sheryl Sandberg,
Facebook COO, is

00:14:53.570 --> 00:14:56.570
learning all about
the power of stories.

00:14:56.570 --> 00:15:00.060
How many of you have
heard of the movement

00:15:00.060 --> 00:15:02.600
that she started, Lean In?

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:04.810
Many of you, most of you now.

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:07.270
Lean In is a very
powerful movement

00:15:07.270 --> 00:15:09.180
for young women
in the workplace.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:12.710
I argue-- and if you'd like
to push back, please do.

00:15:12.710 --> 00:15:14.950
Save your questions
for the Q&amp;A. But I'm

00:15:14.950 --> 00:15:18.160
arguing that you never
would have heard of Lean In,

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:20.460
you would not be
leaning in right now,

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:29.250
if it had not been for a viral
18-minute TEDx presentation

00:15:29.250 --> 00:15:32.330
that Sheryl Sandberg gave that
led to a bestselling book that

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:34.560
eventually sparked the movement.

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:36.990
And here is why it went viral.

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:40.360
Sheryl Sandberg recently
admitted-- just a few months

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:42.990
ago, she talked
about the TED talk

00:15:42.990 --> 00:15:46.100
she gave several years
ago that launched Lean In.

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:50.040
She was ready to give a
talk, in her words, that

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:55.540
was chock full of data
and no personal stories.

00:15:55.540 --> 00:15:57.900
A friend of hers right
before the conference

00:15:57.900 --> 00:15:59.579
pulled her aside
and said, Sheryl,

00:15:59.579 --> 00:16:01.120
you look a little
out of sorts today.

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:02.680
What's going on?

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:04.430
And she said, it's
kind of been a bad day.

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:06.560
Right before I came
out to the conference,

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:08.600
my little girl was
tugging at my leg,

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:11.550
and she was crying and
screaming, mommy don't go.

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:12.980
But it's OK, I'll work it out.

00:16:12.980 --> 00:16:14.540
I'll get it together.

00:16:14.540 --> 00:16:18.710
And her friend said, why don't
you just tell that story?

00:16:18.710 --> 00:16:20.000
Sheryl Sandberg was skeptical.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:21.920
She said, in front of people?

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:24.430
You want me to tell that
story in a presentation?

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:27.300
And then she realized
she had to be vulnerable.

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:31.370
She realized that in order
to touch people emotionally--

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:33.640
isn't that what we're talking
about-- touching people

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:34.990
emotionally?

00:16:34.990 --> 00:16:37.890
She had to break down that
wall and connect with them

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:40.530
on that personal
storytelling level.

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:45.893
Here is how Ms. Sandberg
started her now-famous TED talk.

00:16:45.893 --> 00:16:46.800
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:49.055
-At the outset, I
want to be very clear

00:16:49.055 --> 00:16:51.438
that this speech comes
with no judgments.

00:16:51.438 --> 00:16:52.760
I don't have the right answer.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:55.130
I don't even have it for myself.

00:16:55.130 --> 00:16:58.224
I left San Francisco,
where I live, on Monday.

00:16:58.224 --> 00:17:00.182
I was getting on the
plane for this conference,

00:17:00.182 --> 00:17:02.730
and my daughter, who is
three, when I dropped her off

00:17:02.730 --> 00:17:04.938
at preschool, did that whole
hugging the leg, crying,

00:17:04.938 --> 00:17:06.589
mommy-don't-get-on-the-plane
thing.

00:17:06.589 --> 00:17:08.581
This is hard.

00:17:08.581 --> 00:17:10.573
I feel guilty sometimes.

00:17:10.573 --> 00:17:12.814
I know no women,
whether they're at home

00:17:12.814 --> 00:17:14.806
or whether they're in
the workforce, that

00:17:14.806 --> 00:17:16.550
don't feel that sometimes.

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:18.404
I'm not saying that
staying in the workforce

00:17:18.404 --> 00:17:21.140
is the right thing for everyone.

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:23.890
My talk today is about
what the messages are

00:17:23.890 --> 00:17:26.692
if you want to stay
in the workforce.

00:17:26.692 --> 00:17:28.660
And I think there are three.

00:17:28.660 --> 00:17:31.324
One, sit at the table, two--

00:17:31.324 --> 00:17:32.699
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:17:32.699 --> 00:17:33.740
CARMINE GALLO: The story.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:36.570
It's the story that went viral.

00:17:36.570 --> 00:17:40.260
She applied the same technique
to her book, "Lean In."

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:43.390
Again, the first
chapter was all data.

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:45.250
No personal stories.

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:48.260
Her husband-- true story, she
just said this a few weeks ago.

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:50.690
Her husband read the
first chapter and said,

00:17:50.690 --> 00:17:53.000
this is like eating
your Wheaties.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:58.270
Because we know it's good for
you, but it's kind of boring.

00:17:58.270 --> 00:18:00.550
The book itself is
now full of stories

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:03.540
if you read the first chapter.

00:18:03.540 --> 00:18:07.270
18 minutes leads
to a best seller

00:18:07.270 --> 00:18:11.290
leads to a movement for
millions of young women.

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:16.770
An 18-minute presentation has
the power to start a movement.

00:18:16.770 --> 00:18:19.800
I studied 500 TED talks.

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:22.290
Categorize the content,
and here's what happens.

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:24.250
Pretty fascinating.

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:27.380
Aristotle, for we
communication geeks,

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:29.560
is the father of persuasion.

00:18:29.560 --> 00:18:31.670
He said that
persuasion occurs when

00:18:31.670 --> 00:18:34.090
you have three
components-- pathos, which

00:18:34.090 --> 00:18:37.340
is what we're talking about
now-- emotion, storytelling.

00:18:37.340 --> 00:18:40.010
Logos is data, statistics.

00:18:40.010 --> 00:18:43.270
Ethos is establishing
credibility for who you are.

00:18:43.270 --> 00:18:51.140
65% of the majority of the best
TED talks-- 65% are stories.

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:55.320
25% data, only 10% ethos.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:59.050
Sheryl Sandberg's
talk was 72% stories.

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:03.310
Bryan Stevenson, for example,
tells a lot of stories.

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:06.920
Bryan Stevenson is a
civil rights attorney.

00:19:06.920 --> 00:19:08.930
He knows how to talk to people.

00:19:08.930 --> 00:19:15.100
He successfully wins cases
before the US Supreme Court,

00:19:15.100 --> 00:19:19.420
which, if you haven't guessed,
is a pretty tough audience.

00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:21.490
He knows how to persuade.

00:19:21.490 --> 00:19:24.470
When he gave a TED
talk last year,

00:19:24.470 --> 00:19:28.670
he received the longest
standing ovation at TED.

00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:30.890
I talked to him afterwards.

00:19:30.890 --> 00:19:34.140
He told three stories
from his life.

00:19:34.140 --> 00:19:36.760
He supports the
stories with data,

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:38.400
but the data come
after the stories.

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:43.770
So his template is stories data,
stories data, stories data.

00:19:43.770 --> 00:19:47.160
He includes the data, but
he supports his argument

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:48.560
with stories.

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:51.510
His argument is, as a
civil rights attorney,

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:55.800
that young men and women in
underprivileged and underserved

00:19:55.800 --> 00:20:01.430
communities are incarcerated at
a much higher rate than others.

00:20:01.430 --> 00:20:03.190
That's his theme.

00:20:03.190 --> 00:20:05.740
I want to show you a
clip from this TED talk

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:09.660
because again, he received the
longest standing ovation at TED

00:20:09.660 --> 00:20:11.560
because it was deeply emotional.

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:15.030
Here, he tells a story
about his grandmother.

00:20:15.030 --> 00:20:17.140
I've got to set it
up for just a second.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:20.240
He said that his
grandmother pulled him aside

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:23.580
when he was 11 years
old and said Bryan,

00:20:23.580 --> 00:20:27.260
I want you promise me never
to drink alcohol in your life.

00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:30.170
And Bryan said, well,
OK, I'm only 11.

00:20:30.170 --> 00:20:30.810
So, sure.

00:20:30.810 --> 00:20:33.090
Sure, I'll go along with it.

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:34.970
Here is how he
picks up the story.

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:38.660
His theme, by the way, was
there's power in identity.

00:20:38.660 --> 00:20:44.190
Watch and listen for how the
story reinforces the theme.

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:45.154
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:20:45.154 --> 00:20:47.070
-I grew up in the country,
in the rural South,

00:20:47.070 --> 00:20:50.410
and had a brother a year older
than me and a sister a year

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:50.910
younger.

00:20:50.910 --> 00:20:52.905
I was about 14 or 15
when one day my brother

00:20:52.905 --> 00:20:54.845
came home and had
this six-pack of beer.

00:20:54.845 --> 00:20:56.075
I don't know where he got it.

00:20:56.075 --> 00:20:58.574
And he grabbed me and my sister
and we went out in the woods

00:20:58.574 --> 00:21:00.526
and we were kind of just
out there doing stuff

00:21:00.526 --> 00:21:02.966
we crazily did, and he
had a sip of his beer

00:21:02.966 --> 00:21:04.930
and he gave some to my
sister and she had some,

00:21:04.930 --> 00:21:05.645
and they offered it to me.

00:21:05.645 --> 00:21:06.728
I said, no no no, it's OK.

00:21:06.728 --> 00:21:08.135
Y'all go ahead.

00:21:08.135 --> 00:21:09.426
I'm not going to have any beer.

00:21:09.426 --> 00:21:11.418
And my brother was like, come
on, we're doing this today.

00:21:11.418 --> 00:21:12.414
You always do what we do.

00:21:12.414 --> 00:21:14.406
I had some, your sister
had some, have some beer.

00:21:14.406 --> 00:21:15.900
I said no, I don't
feel right about it.

00:21:15.900 --> 00:21:16.525
Y'all go ahead.

00:21:16.525 --> 00:21:17.394
Y'all go ahead.

00:21:17.394 --> 00:21:18.888
And then my brother
started staring at me.

00:21:18.888 --> 00:21:20.179
He said, what's wrong with you?

00:21:20.179 --> 00:21:21.662
Have some beer.

00:21:21.662 --> 00:21:23.370
And then looked at me
real hard and said,

00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:24.828
oh, I hope you're
not still hung up

00:21:24.828 --> 00:21:28.350
on that conversation
Mama had with you.

00:21:28.350 --> 00:21:30.840
I said, what are
you talking about?

00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:33.688
He says, oh, Mama tells all
grandkids that they're special.

00:21:37.181 --> 00:21:39.809
I was devastated.

00:21:39.809 --> 00:21:41.475
And I'm going to admit
something to you,

00:21:41.475 --> 00:21:45.090
I'm going to tell you something
that I probably shouldn't-- I

00:21:45.090 --> 00:21:47.884
know this might be
broadcast broadly.

00:21:47.884 --> 00:21:50.595
But I'm 52 years
old, and I'm going

00:21:50.595 --> 00:21:54.293
to admit to you that I've
never had a drop of alcohol.

00:21:54.293 --> 00:21:58.730
I don't say that because
I think that's virtuous.

00:21:58.730 --> 00:22:01.688
I say that because there
is power in identity.

00:22:01.688 --> 00:22:03.200
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:04.700
CARMINE GALLO: You
see the template.

00:22:04.700 --> 00:22:07.915
Story ties back to
the central theme.

00:22:07.915 --> 00:22:10.090
There is power in identity.

00:22:10.090 --> 00:22:13.530
Now look, I don't
have all the answers.

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:15.170
I'm constantly
learning something

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:17.190
about communication
and persuasion.

00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:19.640
That's why I talk to
people who, frankly,

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:21.590
are more persuasive than I am.

00:22:21.590 --> 00:22:25.510
If you win Supreme Court cases,
you're pretty persuasive.

00:22:25.510 --> 00:22:27.120
You know how to talk.

00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:30.660
So maybe Bryan Stevenson has
some pretty good answers.

00:22:30.660 --> 00:22:32.400
Maybe we should listen to him.

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:34.860
Storytelling is powerful.

00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:42.250
How many of you enjoy consuming
organic fruits and vegetables?

00:22:42.250 --> 00:22:43.940
Most of you.

00:22:43.940 --> 00:22:46.550
I see downstairs they had
a nice organic section

00:22:46.550 --> 00:22:47.550
of the restaurant.

00:22:47.550 --> 00:22:50.190
You have this woman to thank.

00:22:50.190 --> 00:22:52.440
Her name is Myra Goodman.

00:22:52.440 --> 00:22:55.480
Myra Goodman, several decades
ago with her husband Drew,

00:22:55.480 --> 00:22:57.680
started a two-acre
raspberry farm

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:01.990
and grew it into what is now
Earthbound Farm, the largest

00:23:01.990 --> 00:23:05.770
grower of organic
produce in the world.

00:23:05.770 --> 00:23:07.880
If it wasn't for
her, you probably

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:11.070
would not be having the
abundance of organic

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:14.340
that you do because she
really pioneered the movement.

00:23:14.340 --> 00:23:16.460
She called me in
October and she was

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:19.230
getting ready for a TEDx talk.

00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:22.130
For those of you who don't
know, TEDx are the smaller,

00:23:22.130 --> 00:23:24.880
independently
organized TED events.

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:26.460
She called me in
October and she was

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:32.060
getting ready to talk to this--
it was a food-related event.

00:23:32.060 --> 00:23:34.400
She knew that I had just
finished a book on TED.

00:23:34.400 --> 00:23:36.077
I've known her
for several years.

00:23:36.077 --> 00:23:37.660
She said, what advice
can you give me?

00:23:37.660 --> 00:23:39.680
I said, please
start with stories.

00:23:39.680 --> 00:23:41.230
You've got some great stories.

00:23:41.230 --> 00:23:42.820
You've got good data.

00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:44.910
You've got awesome
data, but we're

00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:47.510
going to wrap that
data in stories.

00:23:47.510 --> 00:23:50.080
For example, I said,
Myra, I love that story

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:52.790
that I remember long
ago when you told me

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:55.905
that you started literally
selling raspberries at a farm

00:23:55.905 --> 00:23:59.660
stand in Carmel, California,
and now you go into every Costco

00:23:59.660 --> 00:24:02.560
and they've got the
entire section of organic.

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:06.710
Here's how she
started her TEDx talk.

00:24:06.710 --> 00:24:08.960
I think it was-- actually,
it was just a few weeks ago

00:24:08.960 --> 00:24:09.859
in March.

00:24:09.859 --> 00:24:10.837
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

