00:25:59.030 --> 00:26:02.150
"Ideas That Spread,"
teach me something new.

00:26:02.150 --> 00:26:05.720
Teach me something that
I've never heard before.

00:26:05.720 --> 00:26:08.690
Something new,
unexpected, or surprising.

00:26:08.690 --> 00:26:10.360
There's science behind this.

00:26:10.360 --> 00:26:13.800
Dr. A.K. Pradeep, who is a
neuroscientist in Berkeley,

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:17.990
said that our brains are
trained to look for something

00:26:17.990 --> 00:26:20.940
brilliant and new,
something that stands out,

00:26:20.940 --> 00:26:23.590
something that looks delicious.

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:29.340
When the brain detects something
new, surprising, shocking,

00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:32.260
unexpected, it
literally releases

00:26:32.260 --> 00:26:37.220
dopamine, which acts as
a mental save button.

00:26:37.220 --> 00:26:38.800
I interviewed Robert Ballard.

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:40.870
Robert Ballard
discovered a little ship

00:26:40.870 --> 00:26:44.590
