00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:38.730
Those were extreme.

00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:40.885
But what did he do?

00:32:40.885 --> 00:32:42.639
Oh, but there is one more thing.

00:32:42.639 --> 00:32:44.930
When he first did that, that
was completely surprising,

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:47.070
completely unexpected.

00:32:47.070 --> 00:32:50.070
Steve Jobs was brilliant at
that and incorporating something

00:32:50.070 --> 00:32:53.510
new and novel into every
one of his keynotes.

00:32:53.510 --> 00:32:57.330
Finally, the brain
has to remember it.

00:32:57.330 --> 00:32:58.330
It doesn't matter.

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:00.970
Your idea, your
presentation, the beautiful

00:33:00.970 --> 00:33:03.080
slides-- it's not
going to matter

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:06.320
if I don't remember the content.

00:33:06.320 --> 00:33:08.640
Let me give you some
very specific techniques

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:11.280
on making your pitch
more memorable.

00:33:11.280 --> 00:33:13.710
All TED talks, as
you probably know,

00:33:13.710 --> 00:33:15.730
are limited to 18 minutes.

00:33:15.730 --> 00:33:17.220
The 18 minute rule.

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:20.710
It doesn't matter whether your
name is Bill Gates, Sheryl

00:33:20.710 --> 00:33:23.260
Sandberg, or this week, Sting.

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:25.210
Sting talked, last
year was Bono.

00:33:25.210 --> 00:33:26.790
Doesn't matter who you are.

00:33:26.790 --> 00:33:28.760
You're only limited
to 18 minutes.

00:33:28.760 --> 00:33:32.210
That's not a bad time limit.

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:34.390
In fact, the TED
organizers found

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:37.800
that 18 minutes is long enough
to have a serious discussion

00:33:37.800 --> 00:33:40.160
and short enough to
keep people's attention.

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:44.030
There's science behind this
that you as communicators

00:33:44.030 --> 00:33:45.050
need to know.

00:33:45.050 --> 00:33:47.550
It's called cognitive back log.

00:33:47.550 --> 00:33:50.940
Researchers at Texas Christian
University are working on this.

00:33:50.940 --> 00:33:53.480
It simply means that
if I ask you retain

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:56.900
more information, the more
information I pile on,

00:33:56.900 --> 00:33:58.350
like weights,
pretty soon, you're

00:33:58.350 --> 00:33:59.910
going to drop the whole thing.

00:33:59.910 --> 00:34:02.120
Cognitive back log.

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:03.920
In fact, they're
finding-- depending

00:34:03.920 --> 00:34:09.210
on the research-- anywhere from
about 10 minutes to 18 minutes,

00:34:09.210 --> 00:34:11.210
people start losing attention.

00:34:11.210 --> 00:34:13.980
They actually will physically
start looking at their watch,

00:34:13.980 --> 00:34:15.550
look at their
phones, and thinking

00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:17.199
about what they're
going to do next.

00:34:17.199 --> 00:34:18.860
From 10 to 18 minutes.

00:34:18.860 --> 00:34:21.960
So during that time, you
need to reengage them.

00:34:21.960 --> 00:34:23.376
I'm going to speak
for-- I'm going

00:34:23.376 --> 00:34:24.780
to break the 18 minute rule.

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:26.692
I'm going to speak for
more than 18 minutes.

00:34:26.692 --> 00:34:27.900
We're going to break that up.

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:30.489
We're going to have some Q&amp;A
so it's not just me speaking.

00:34:30.489 --> 00:34:34.260
I'm trying to add video
clips so there's two voices.

00:34:34.260 --> 00:34:36.690
Those are different
ways of reengaging.

00:34:36.690 --> 00:34:40.110
But if I were to just stand
here with no visual display

00:34:40.110 --> 00:34:44.130
of content, no information,
no second speaker

00:34:44.130 --> 00:34:46.520
and I just talked
to you, by now,

00:34:46.520 --> 00:34:48.310
you'd be ready to
tear your hair out,

00:34:48.310 --> 00:34:50.840
no matter how engaging a
speaker you think you are.

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:56.060
The brain naturally tunes out
after about 10 to 18 minutes.

00:34:56.060 --> 00:34:57.520
That's a very powerful concept.

00:34:57.520 --> 00:34:58.950
It's very important
to understand

00:34:58.950 --> 00:35:01.390
when you're giving a
pitch or a presentation.

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:04.650
A lot of great things
can happen in 18 minutes.

00:35:04.650 --> 00:35:06.850
John Kennedy inspired
a nation to look

00:35:06.850 --> 00:35:09.800
to the stars in 15 minutes.

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:11.870
Steve Jobs gave one of
the greatest commencement

00:35:11.870 --> 00:35:13.550
addresses of our
time at Stanford.

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:15.620
That was 15 minutes.

00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:18.500
Martin Luther King, he
took a little extra time

00:35:18.500 --> 00:35:21.590
to outline his vision
for racial equality.

00:35:21.590 --> 00:35:23.530
That took about 17 minutes.

00:35:23.530 --> 00:35:27.180
Sheryl Sandberg started a
movement is about 16 minutes.

00:35:27.180 --> 00:35:29.030
Al Gore's "An
Inconvenient Truth"

00:35:29.030 --> 00:35:31.880
was originally a TED talk.

00:35:31.880 --> 00:35:34.470
Launched the whole
global warming thing.

00:35:34.470 --> 00:35:36.910
A lot of initiatives,
movements can

00:35:36.910 --> 00:35:40.710
start in as little
as 18 minutes.

00:35:40.710 --> 00:35:45.590
Think about keeping
your content concise.

00:35:45.590 --> 00:35:48.400
And then think about this other
technique that is so powerful.

00:35:48.400 --> 00:35:50.504
It works almost every time.

00:35:50.504 --> 00:35:52.170
I'm not going to
guarantee you anything,

00:35:52.170 --> 00:35:55.730
but this is close--
the rule of three.

00:35:55.730 --> 00:36:00.370
The rule of three means that in
short term or working memory,

00:36:00.370 --> 00:36:04.860
you're only capable of caring
about three big ideas, three

00:36:04.860 --> 00:36:06.460
chunks of information.

00:36:06.460 --> 00:36:08.220
If I ask you to
remember a phone number,

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:12.340
you divide up into
chunks of three and four.

00:36:12.340 --> 00:36:14.530
Threes is a very
powerful number.

00:36:14.530 --> 00:36:17.090
It pervades every
aspect of our society.

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:21.040
From slogans like "Just Do
It," or Obama's "Yes We Can."

00:36:21.040 --> 00:36:24.790
Company names-- SAP, IBM, CNN.

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:27.370
And certainly literature-- "The
Three Musketeers," "The Three

00:36:27.370 --> 00:36:30.250
Little Pigs," "The Three Bears."

00:36:30.250 --> 00:36:31.180
The rule of three.

00:36:31.180 --> 00:36:33.940
Authors know this
very, very well.

00:36:33.940 --> 00:36:35.820
Writers know this very well.

00:36:35.820 --> 00:36:38.190
Great presenters
know it very well.

00:36:38.190 --> 00:36:41.050
Bryan Stevenson
told three stories.

00:36:41.050 --> 00:36:45.260
He did not tell 12 or two.

00:36:45.260 --> 00:36:46.870
Told three.

00:36:46.870 --> 00:36:48.800
It's an important number.

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:52.940
The brain needs more than
one, but after you give it

00:36:52.940 --> 00:36:55.250
about five, six,
or seven points,

00:36:55.250 --> 00:36:56.730
it starts to forget everything.

00:36:56.730 --> 00:36:59.630
Three is a really good number.

00:36:59.630 --> 00:37:02.530
Tell your boss there's
three reasons why

00:37:02.530 --> 00:37:03.980
you should back my idea.

00:37:03.980 --> 00:37:05.540
There's three reasons.

00:37:05.540 --> 00:37:07.640
There's three new
features of this product

00:37:07.640 --> 00:37:09.910
that I think our consumers
are going to like.

00:37:09.910 --> 00:37:13.320
When I was analyzing all the
TED talks, take a look at this.

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:16.900
These are just some examples
of the rule of three

00:37:16.900 --> 00:37:19.430
from the best TED talks.

00:37:19.430 --> 00:37:21.860
Three reasons why
videos go viral.

00:37:21.860 --> 00:37:23.850
These, by the way,
are not necessarily

00:37:23.850 --> 00:37:26.910
the titles-- some of them are,
but most of them are not--

00:37:26.910 --> 00:37:29.380
but it's the theme of
the actual presentation.

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:31.910
Three reasons why
videos go viral.

00:37:31.910 --> 00:37:35.200
Three ways design
makes you happy.

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:37.520
Three ways the brain
creates meaning.

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:39.920
Three clues to
understanding your brain.

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:41.712
A lot of brain stuff.

00:37:41.712 --> 00:37:43.004
AUDIENCE: That was four things.

00:37:43.004 --> 00:37:44.212
CARMINE GALLO: That was four.

00:37:44.212 --> 00:37:45.340
There was a bullet of four.

00:37:45.340 --> 00:37:46.790
But there's more.

00:37:46.790 --> 00:37:50.970
Three ways brands lose control.

00:37:50.970 --> 00:37:53.700
Three ways crooks steal
your digital data.

00:37:53.700 --> 00:37:56.730
Three myths about big organic.

00:37:56.730 --> 00:38:00.220
And of course, three things I
learned when my plane crashed.

00:38:00.220 --> 00:38:01.420
The rule of three.

00:38:01.420 --> 00:38:03.080
Very, very powerful.

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:05.070
I do a lot of what's
called media training,

00:38:05.070 --> 00:38:07.310
so I work with executives
before they go on

00:38:07.310 --> 00:38:09.920
to import media interviews.

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:12.690
Three always works.

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:15.070
I hate to sound
too manipulative,

00:38:15.070 --> 00:38:16.680
but this is how the brain works.

00:38:16.680 --> 00:38:20.300
If you give people three things
that they need to keep in mind,

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:21.390
they'll write them down.

00:38:21.390 --> 00:38:23.436
They want to know,
what's the third?

00:38:23.436 --> 00:38:24.310
Or what's the second?

00:38:24.310 --> 00:38:25.610
Did I miss the second one?

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:27.720
People cannot ignore lists.

00:38:27.720 --> 00:38:29.370
Three is a good list.

00:38:29.370 --> 00:38:32.420
And finally, to make it
memorable-- especially

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:35.320
when we're delivering it doesn't
matter what software you use,

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:38.420
either Google software or
traditional PowerPoint,

00:38:38.420 --> 00:38:42.580
or I use Apple Keynote or
Prezzie, think visually.

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:43.900
Think visually.

00:38:43.900 --> 00:38:46.710
This is called
picture superiority.

00:38:46.710 --> 00:38:49.940
Picture superiority means
that if I deliver content

00:38:49.940 --> 00:38:54.600
to you verbally, you'll remember
about 10% of the content.

00:38:54.600 --> 00:39:01.200
If I add a picture or an
image, retention soars to 65%.

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:05.220
The average PowerPoint
has 40 words.

00:39:05.220 --> 00:39:08.520
Several years ago, when I
started analyzing Steve Jobs'

00:39:08.520 --> 00:39:10.170
presentations--
and again, I think

00:39:10.170 --> 00:39:13.240
we'll all acknowledge he was
the original great corporate

00:39:13.240 --> 00:39:19.240
storyteller-- I never found one
slide, never, with 40 words.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:24.525
In fact, on average, it took
him 10 slides to reach 40 words.

00:39:24.525 --> 00:39:29.150
It was all pictures,
images that spoke so much

00:39:29.150 --> 00:39:30.930
more than any text could.

00:39:30.930 --> 00:39:33.520
When you're talking about a new
computer like the MacBook Air

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:37.860
and you want to talk about how
thin it is, no number of words

00:39:37.860 --> 00:39:40.560
could describe it
like that photograph.

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:44.990
So thin it fits inside
an office envelope.

00:39:44.990 --> 00:39:47.770
When you watch some of the great
TED presentations-- and Bono

00:39:47.770 --> 00:39:50.130
did a beautiful one that
you can go onto TED.com

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:53.150
to watch-- that was
created in Prezzie.

00:39:53.150 --> 00:39:55.050
Beautifully done.

00:39:55.050 --> 00:39:58.430
Some data, mostly
images and pictures

00:39:58.430 --> 00:39:59.810
that supported the data.

00:39:59.810 --> 00:40:05.260
Steve Jobs, his PowerPoints
are very unlike anything

00:40:05.260 --> 00:40:08.090
that you used to see
from him and Microsoft.

00:40:08.090 --> 00:40:12.350
They're very visual, this whole
idea of picture superiority.

00:40:12.350 --> 00:40:15.330
Whenever you see
major executives now

00:40:15.330 --> 00:40:18.920
give presentations-- maybe
not internally, but certainly

00:40:18.920 --> 00:40:22.310
to external customers
and at external events--

00:40:22.310 --> 00:40:25.660
they're are all
using this style.

00:40:25.660 --> 00:40:28.980
Whether it's Google-- I've seen
a number of executives using

00:40:28.980 --> 00:40:31.960
this style-- Marissa Mayer
is now using it at Yahoo.

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:34.140
She's building
beautiful presentations

00:40:34.140 --> 00:40:36.100
if you saw her at CES.

00:40:36.100 --> 00:40:37.530
Actually, she was doing it here.

00:40:37.530 --> 00:40:40.610
She was still doing it here.

00:40:40.610 --> 00:40:43.720
Zuckerberg over at Facebook,
and Apple, certainly, they

00:40:43.720 --> 00:40:45.320
continue to use this style.

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:47.670
It's more of a visual style.

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:49.070
You need to think visually.

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:52.320
This is an actual slide from
Bill Gates' slide, where

00:40:52.320 --> 00:40:56.130
